Explore the diamonds data

Task: Use R to produce one informative graphic of the diamonds data. The graphic should represent AT LEAST 3 variables. Write a few sentences to describe what we can learn from the graphic your have provided. (Note: please do NOT write your narrative inside the code chunk.)

# read `diamonds` data into R; it has been provided by the `ggplot2` package
data("diamonds", package = "ggplot2")

# add your code below for your one key data visualization
ggplot(diamonds) +
  aes(x = carat, y = price) +
  geom_point(shape = "circle", size = 1.5, colour = "#112446") +
  theme_bw() +
  facet_wrap(vars(cut))

The dataset represents 54000 diamonds in terms of different attributes. One case demonstrates one diamond with its attributes. For example, price means price in US dollars. Carat represents weight of the diamond. Cut represents the quality of the cut. My graph chooses carat, price, and cut as variables. I put carat as x-axis, price as y-axis, and cut as facet. The scatter plot graph shows the correlation between carat and price in terms of different cut. We can see the correlation is weakest while cut is fair.

Explore the cereal data

Task: Use R to produce one informative graphic of the cereal.csv data. The graphic should represent AT LEAST 3 variables. Write a few sentences to describe what we can learn from the graphic your have provided. (Note: please do NOT write your narrative inside the code chunk.)

# read CSV data set into R
CerealData <- readr::read_csv(file = "cereal.csv")  
## Rows: 77 Columns: 16
##  Column specification 
## Delimiter: ","
## chr  (3): name, mfr, type
## dbl (13): calories, protein, fat, sodium, fiber, carbo, sugars, potass, vita...
## 
##  Use `spec()` to retrieve the full column specification for this data.
##  Specify the column types or set `show_col_types = FALSE` to quiet this message.
# add your code below for your one key data visualization

ggplot(CerealData) +
  aes(x = calories, y = rating) +
  geom_point(shape = "circle", size = 1.5, colour = "#112446") +
  theme_bw() +
  facet_wrap(vars(mfr))

The dataset represents different types of cereal in terms of nutrition data. Each case reprents a type of cereal in different variables. For example, I choose calories, the calories per serving, rating, a rating of the cereals, and mfr, the manufacture of cereal as my variables in my graph. I put calories as x-axis, rating as y-axis, and mfr as facet. From the scatter plot graph, I can know that the less calories cereal has, the more rating it will get whatever the manufacture it is.

Extension: programming style

The helper functions are great, but they produce ugly code. Clean up the ggplot2 code that reproduces the required plots so that it aligns with the R Programming Style Guide Appendix in the DataComputing eBook https://dtkaplan.github.io/DataComputingEbook/.
